\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Illustration of Euclidean projection versus Mahalanobis projection under an anisotropic GNSS covariance ellipse. The red point denotes the GNSS observation $z_i$; the yellow point is the Euclidean (orthogonal) projection onto the road segment; the green point is the Mahalanobis projection that minimizes the covariance-weighted distance. Because the GNSS error ellipse is elongated, the Mahalanobis projection correctly selects the candidate aligned with the principal axis of uncertainty, whereas the Euclidean projection incorrectly favors the geometrically closest point.}}{7}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:measprob}{{7}{7}}
